comment_text: Tesla is a disruptive company, rethinking and executing on many fronts - energy, manufacturing, science, etc. What we are witnessing is a generational shift in how things are done. Combine this with a CEO that has the foresight to understand the global picture of financial sustainability and path that America is on (bankruptcy due to continued growth in debt), you HAVE TO MAKE CHANGES when you spend more than you earn. Change is scary. It brings pain. People will be upset. Does Elon rub many people the wrong way? Yes! But that is what happens when you focus on fixing a broken system the size of the US govt. Government programs need to be audited just like public and private companies in order to protect the investment of the owners (taxpayers). Whether it‚Äôs Elon or someone else, our government spending needs to be lean and efficient. Gone are the days of funding pet projects with taxpayer dollars that line the pockets of a select few and don‚Äôt benefit the taxpayers. Thank you Elon for stepping up. Has his involvement with DOGE changed the great work that Tesla is doing? NO! Is there a short term impact on the brand and stock value? YES, but it will recover. IMO this is a marathon, not a sprint.

comment_text: Tesla recently released its Full Self-Driving (FSD) software package in China. However, the FSD functionality has not been implemented in the majority of vehicles equipped with the 3.0 hardware, Instead, it is only available on a small portion of vehicles with the 4.0 hardware. Despite this, Tesla has been misleading consumers who already own vehicles with the 3.0 hardware and have purchased the 32,000 RMB assisted driving package, encouraging them to spend an additional 32,000 RMB on the FSD software package, which offers no functionality for their vehicles. Tesla has also refused to issue refunds. On the mobile app for vehicles with the 3.0 hardware, the purchase of the FSD package is shown as successful, and the vehicle's system displays a successful upgrade. However, the vehicles do not actually possess full self-driving capabilities. This has led many 3.0 hardware owners in mainland China to mistakenly believe their vehicles are equipped with FSD functionality, resulting in numerous traffic violations such as running red lights, crossing lanes, and even car accidents. This poses a significant threat to the safety of consumers in mainland China and constitutes malicious exploitation and fraudulent behavior by Tesla.

comment_text: A Tesla Nissan tie up might not be a bad business move. When Tesla would always contact me about moving to California or Texas, I would remind him that in the Southeast USA there is a huge part supplier network for most OEMs and that Trump plays golf in Florida and not Texas with the Armadillo. Also, mostly nonunion and Republican which is Trump base. Now a new Tesla plant would be expensive but joining up with Nissan would make this unnecessary. Tesla is one dimensional in the car business with only BEVs and you have to be able to bend with the wind when EVs are out of favor for a while or get killed on sales. Nissan has a major presence in Japan and Detroit. Nissan is in need of cash and not as much debt as Renault. Could use Tesla BEV knowledge to develop their EV lineup and couldn‚Äôt hurt making their Infiniti models more up to date. Would give Nissan a bigger foothold in the California market and Tesla technology advancements. Would help Nissan erase the legacy of Carlos and maybe improve their quality which had been slipping from his term at Nissan. Nissan is trying to lure the younger population into buying their cars and with a Tesla tie up, they should be able to sell more to the Millennials in the USA & Japan.

comment_text: The success criteria for self-driving cars CANNOT be perfect safety. The criteria MUST be: statistically at least as safe as human drivers. And that‚Äôs actually not a very high bar. Human drivers cause an ESTIMATED six million accidents per year in the US‚Ä¶ so many that nobody knows the exact number. Those accidents result in about 38,000 deaths and 4.7 million hospitalizations per year. It‚Äôs about 1.3 deaths per 100-million-vehicle-miles-traveled (100MVMT), about 1850 accidents per 100MVMT. Tesla cars have already driven over 3.3 billion miles on FDS or Autopilot. Their at-fault accident rate is about 441 per 100MVMT, less than one-quarter that of human drivers. The fatality rate is about 0.2 per 100MVMT, less than one-sixth that of human drivers! Already, Tesla‚Äôs self-driving is statistically MUCH safer than humans, 4-6 times safer. And Tesla‚Äôs algorithms literally get better every day. Self-driving cars are not the problem; they are the solution. Hopefully, politicians won‚Äôt deny us that solution because of some neoluddism. By the way, drunk drivers cause about 1/3 of traffic accident fatalities; it‚Äôs not perfect ‚Äî yet ‚Äî but at least Autopilot doesn‚Äôt drink.

comment_text: Once this goes live, I think, over time, it will become super popular as a service and as car ownership. Now you can wake up early get into your car and sleep until you get there. Or after a long day on set, hop into your car and sleep on the way home. People are resistant, but once you begin to realize you don't have to be so aware of everything while you drive and can simply relax, it's kind of epic. Seriously have you ever driven someplace and during your trip realize that you weren't paying very close attention on the last few streets? And kind of shake yourself to pay closer attention? I've been driving for so many years, sometimes you gloss over the details, which is so close to the moment you'll hit something or run that red light or not look carefully when you're backing up. I can't wait. The first time I tested it, I was angry. It was so nerve wracking that I thought it was 5 years away. I had a month free test. But once the free test was almost over. I began to realize how much less stressful driving had become. I could see that I would definitely rather have a more relaxed drive experience than normal. I predict this will be everyone's experience.

comment_text: Shame on Tesla! Tesla recently released its Full Self-Driving (FSD) software package in China. However, the FSD functionality has not been implemented in the majority of vehicles equipped with the 3.0 hardware, Instead, it is only available on a small portion of vehicles with the 4.0 hardware. Tesla has been misleading consumers who already own vehicles with the 3.0 hardware and have purchased the 32,000 RMB assisted driving package, encouraging them to spend an additional 32,000 RMB on the FSD software package, which offers no functionality for their vehicles. Tesla has also refused to issue refunds. On the mobile app for vehicles with the 3.0 hardware, the purchase of the FSD package is shown as successful, and the vehicle's system displays a successful upgrade. However, the vehicles do not actually possess full self-driving capabilities. This has led many 3.0 hardware owners in mainland China to mistakenly believe their vehicles are equipped with FSD functionality, resulting in numerous traffic violations such as running red lights, crossing lanes, and even car accidents. This poses a significant threat to the safety of consumers in mainland China and constitutes malicious exploitation and fraudulent behavior by Tesla.

comment_text: Cyber truck attacked! How can this be true? Is this a joke? When you‚Äôve failed on the most basic safety features of a car, literally? Before you test your car with any protocols, I think you should check the basic safety features first. For instance, people should be able to open doors without getting destroyed their fingers, and it would be common sense. I have proof to show that this truck literally destroyed my finger.
